<DOC><DOCNO> AP890602-0100 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 1117EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Spain     06-02 0272</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Spain,0279</SECOND><HEAD>Rail Workers Smash Windows During Strike for Better Pay</HEAD><DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Government rail workers went on a one-daystrike for better pay today and smashed windows, cut power linesand blocked railroad tracks, authorities said.   The walkout is the latest labor dispute involving state employeegroups opposed to the Socialist administration's efforts to keeppay levels down to contain inflation.   Also today, workers at the state-run Spanish Television monopolyended at midday their 24-hour strike for improved pay. The strikeleft many of Spain's television screens showing only test patterns.   One-day strikes today also were under way at the state telephonemonopoly and the government mint, union and company officials said.   The RENFE state railroad reported that rail workers disruptedservice during their strike, which began at midnight and involves63,000 workers.   Workers delayed the departure out of Madrid and Barcelona ofseveral long-distance trains for up to 90 minutes early today andtemporarily blocked rail lines in the northern cities ofValladolid, Zaragoza and Miranda de Ebro.   Pickets also delayed four short-run trains out of Madrid bysmashing numerous windows, RENFE said. The company also saidpickets in Zaragoza had cut power cables near the city's trainstation.   The company also said 30 percent to 50 percent of regularcommuter trains ran in the major cities but only during the morningand afternoon rush hours.   A television union official, Joaquin Aguilar, said on Thursdaythe only exceptions permitted to the total blackout were four20-minute newscasts, followed by obligatory public service campaignspots for the June 15 European parliamentary elections and an hourof children's cartoons.</TEXT></DOC>